@encukou Ok about `'wb'`, the convenience argument can be enough. Agree about author names, paths, ...

@pyos I think you are right.

In any case the behaviour will be the same for Python 2 and 3.

At the end Vicent may be right. Maybe it is better to make an extension type like this:

```
typedef struct {
    PyObject_HEAD
    PyObject *filename;
    PyObject *attributes;
    PyObject *oid;
} TreeEntry;
```

Thoughts?

Actually, here's a decent workaround I found.

``` c
diff --git a/pygit2.c b/pygit2.c
index c4744b4..60605b8 100644
--- a/pygit2.c
+++ b/pygit2.c
@@ -49,8 +49,13 @@
 Py_LOCAL_INLINE(PyObject*)
 to_unicode(const char *value, const char *encoding, const char *errors)
 {
-    if (encoding == NULL)
+    if (encoding == NULL) {
+        /* If the encoding isn't known, it may not be UTF-8, so it is
+         * not safe to decode it strictly.  We see this in old
+         * commits. */
         encoding = "utf-8";
+        errors = "replace";
+    }
     return PyUnicode_Decode(value, strlen(value), encoding, errors);
 }
```

I went through the code I have which uses pygit2, looking for real usage of tree entries. I only found one, it is a general case of `git_tree_get_subtree` : from a tree and a path returns an object (tree or blob), or `None`. This code only accesses `tenry.oid` (once), so making all three attributes into Python objects would not help. Though, this is not enough to make any decision.

The other alternative would be something like :

```
typedef struct {
    PyObject_HEAD
    PyObject *owner;
    git_tree_entry *entry;
} TreeEntry;
```

And then do type-checking on the owner (tree or tree-builder).

the code below looks suspect; does this work correctly if the owner is a tree builder? Is this method necessary? If you have the repo at hand, in python, you can just do 

 repo[entry.hex]

maybe it's better to drop this method. Also stylistically, doing 

 Repository\* repo = bla->repo;

is shorter and more robust (no program states with uninitialized memory).

TreeEntry_to_object(TreeEntry *self)
 {
     const git_oid *entry_oid;
-    Repository *repo;
-    repo = ((Object*)(self->owner))->repo;
   entry_oid = git_tree_entry_id(self->entry);
-    return lookup_object(self->repo, entry_oid, GIT_OBJ_ANY);
-    return lookup_object(repo, entry_oid, GIT_OBJ_ANY);
  }

